The pipeline structures computer vision into five sequential stages, moving hierarchically from raw data ingestion to high-level semantic reasoning.

Data Acquisition serves as the foundation, capturing environmental signals through modalities like cameras and LiDAR, grounded in classic vision frameworks like David Marr's theory.

Pre-processing refines this raw input via noise reduction, geometric transformations, and initial segmentation to ensure data consistency, leaning on fundamental image processing literature (e.g., Gonzalez & Woods).

Feature Extraction bridges the gap from pixels to patterns, transitioning from low-level edges (SIFT) to deep, high-level representations (AlexNet) to reduce dimensionality.

Analysis & Interpretation acts as the mid-level processing hub, identifying and localizing entities using seminal object detection architectures like YOLO and Faster R-CNN.

The final stage, Semantic Reasoning, synthesizes these detections into deep context, analyzing activities, actions, and complex real-world relationships.

This high-level reasoning culminates in actionable, meaningful outputs such as semantic segmentation maps, event triggers, and structured data graphs.

Continuous feedback loops route information from downstream reasoning back to earlier stages, allowing the system to refine its models dynamically over time.

Supporting the entire pipeline are unified dependencies, including hardware compute resources (GPUs/CPUs) and foundational datasets like ImageNet and MS COCO.

Ultimately, the map demonstrates how computer vision transforms unstructured, noisy physical light into structured, intelligent digital decisions through a collaborative chain of academic breakthroughs.
